			<ns0:name>mcgra...@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/109286297231979736865/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The x86 instructions {movs,stos,cmps}[blwq] take no explicit operands and implicitly use registers SI and/or DI as addresses for memory reference.  Hence, on x86-64 these instructions read from and/or write to the address in %rsi and/or %rdi.  There is no way to make these instructions add in %r15, so we must refuse them from validation.

The validator currently accepts these.  That leaves a trivially-exploitable hole to access any memory address in the low 4GB (and above it if you can start at 0xffffffff and not fault).</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2011-08-31T20:18:47.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2011-08-31T18:33:26.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Invalid</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
